The EFF leader appeared in court on charges of contravening the Riotous Assemblies Act. He faces a similar case in Newcastle. JOHANNESBURG - The land grab case against Economic Freedom Fighters (EFF) leader Julius Malema has been postponed to October this year.Malema appeared in the Bloemfontein Magistrates Court on Monday on charges of contravening the Riotous Assemblies Act.It relates to comments he made at the EFF's 2014 elective conference, where he instructed members to occupy vacant land wherever they find it.The red beret leader was also charged for similar remarks he made in Newcastle. That case has also been postponed to October this year to allow his legal team time to challenge the constitutionality of the act.(Edited by Zinhle Nkosi)